Steffimycin  and  steffimycin  B,  derived  from  Streptomyces  steffiburgensis  and  S.  elgreteus, respectively (Figure 1 ), are anthracycline antibiotics with antitumor activities  (1,2). Their chemical structures are grossly similar to the clinically important drugs  daunorubicin (daunomycin) and doxorubicin ( adriamycin) in that they all contain  a single sugar moiety attached to the ring A of the aglycone chromophore at the C7  position (Figure 1 ). However these anthracyclines differ in details, e.g., in having a  different chirality ofC9 atom with respect to its attached hydroxyl group. In daunorubicin  and doxorubicin, the functionally essential 09 hydroxyl group is in the axial position  and on the same side as the 07 hydroxyl group of ring A; whereas in steffimycin it is  in the equatorial position. In addition, the exocyclic positions on the aglycone rings

The molecular and crystal structure of steffimycin have been determined by single crystal X  ray diffraction to 0.9 A resolution. The triclinic crystals are in the space group PI, with the unit  cell  dimensions  of a=8.606(3) A  b=22.168(7)  A c=8.448(2) A  a=97.56(3}",  ~=95.97(2)",  y= 87.94(3)", Z= 2. The structure was solved by direct methods and refined by the full-matrix  least-squares method to a final R value of0.065 with 3405 Onet  > 2.0 cr(lneJ) observed reflections  using the NRCVAX software package. The crystal lattice includes 2 independent steffimycin,  3 water  and one 2-methyl-2,4-pentanediol  molecules.  The  conformation of steffimycin  is  grossly similar to other anthracycline antibiotics including daunorubicin. The crystal packing  interactions of steffimycin suggest a preferred stacking of the aglycone chromophore of the  antibiotic which resembles the intercalative interactions seen in the daunorubicin-d(CGTACG)  (Wang eta!., Biochemistry 26,  1152 (1987))  and nogalamycin-d(CGT(pS)ACG) (Liaw eta!.,  Biochemistry 28,9913 (1989)) complexes. The atomic coordinates data from these complexes  were used to model the intercalative binding of steffimycin to DNA The models were then  stereochemically idealized by the constraint refinement program NUCLSQ. Subsequently  XPLOR software package was used for energy minimization of these models in  vacuo. The  model building studies suggest that steffimycin has a higher CpG base sequence specificity  over the TpA step, similar to that of daunorubicin and nogalamycin. Attempts to crystallize  the complexes ofboth compounds with different DNA oligonucleotides were made.  Most of them did not crystallize. Only the steffimycin-d(GCGTACGC) complex  formed large tetragonal bipyramid crystals which have the unit cell dimensions of  a=b=48.4 A and c=22.0 A. Unfortunately, these crystals diffract x-rays to very low  resolution ( ~6A) and were not studied further. However, during our crystallization  screening process we observed some crystals of rectangular plates in cluster forms  This structural database of crystal  structures  permits us  to  contemplate ways  in  which other anthracyclines may bind to DNA double helix, on the basis ofthe three  dimensional structure of free drugs only. The emerging general picture shows that the  elongated aglycone chromophore of anthracycline antibiotics intercalate between the  CG base pairs of the CpG dinucleotide step with the sugars lying in the grooves of the  distorted B-DNAdouble helix. Hydrogen bonds are found in the complex between the  drugs and guanine bases to anchor the drug molecule in a specific orientation.  Steffimycin and Its Binding to DNA

It has been demonstrated by spectroscopic and thermal stabilization studies (3,4) that  steffimycin analogs bind to DNA like other anthracycline antibiotics. Anthracycline  antitumor drugs have been shown to bind to DNA by intercalation into the DNA  double  helix using  their aromatic  aglycone  chromophores  (5-7).  The  biological  activities of these antitumor drugs are believed to be closely associated with their  DNA binding  ability.  The  detailed  interactions  between  various  anthracycline  drugs  (including  daunorubicin  (8,9),  doxorubicin  (10),  nogalamycin,  and  their  derivatives ( 11-13) and several DNA hexamers have been studied by high resolution  x-ray diffraction analysis and two dimensional NMR (14,15). The results have provided  valuable information regarding the role of various functional groups of the drug  molecules (5-7). The structural studies have further shown that the drug molecules  in  general  retain  their  conformational  rigidity  when  they  are  bound  to  DNA  Nevertheless, limited flexibilities exist in the drug molecules: the dihedral angles of  the glycosyl bond associated with the C7 atom in ring A, the pucker of ring A itself  and finally the ability of rings B-D to bend gently (16).  In this paper, we describe the three dimensional molecular structure of steffimycin  which has been determined in a hydrated environment at atomic resolution by x  ray diffraction. The structure is compared to that of the steffimycin B ( 17). Finally a  plausible model is  constructed for the binding preference of steffimycin to  DNA  based on the available structural information, and evaluated.  A-D are associated with different substituents. Finally, steffimycin is more hydrophobic  with limited solubility in aqueous solution, in contrast to the hydrochloride salts of  daunorubicin and doxorubicin which are readily soluble in water, likely in part due  to the positively charged amino sugar.

The best crystals appeared from  a crystallization mixture contained 0.8  mM of oligonucleotide d(CGTACGh 8 mM  MgC12, 30 mM sodium cacodylate (pH 6), 1.6 mM steffimycin in 10%(v/v) 2-methyl-2,4- pentanediol (2-MPD) equilibrated with  30%  2-MPD by the vapor diffusion  method. The crystal is in the space group P 1 with unit cell dimensions a= 8.606(3) A b = 22.168(7)  A c=8.448(2) A a=97.56(3)",  ~=95.97(2)", y=87.94(3)". A crystal with  the size of  0.05 X 0.2 X 0.7 mm was mounted in a sealed glass capillary with a droplet of mother  liquor for data collection on the same diffractometer at 25 ac using the ffi-scan mode  with graphite monochromated CuKa radiation. Data were collected to a resolution  of 0.9 A (29= 120°), with  h,  k,  1,  ranges  -8 to 8,  -22 to 21  and 0 to 8 respectively.  Lorentz-polarization, empirical absorption, and decay corrections were applied to  the data.

The structure was solved by the direct method using the program SHELXS86 (18)  and  refined  by  the  full-matrix  least-square  refinement  package  NRCVAX  (19).  Initially, two  independent steffimycin molecules (denoted STEF-l and STEF-11)  were found from the first E-Map. Subsequently, three water molecules and one 2- MPD molecule were located from a series of (Fo-Fc) difference Fourier maps and  they were included in the refinement. Refinement with isotropic temperature factors of  those atoms resulted in an R-factor (I: II Fo 1-1 Fe II /I: I Fo I) of 11.6% using the 3405  observed  reflections  (lnet>2.0  a(lnet)).  The  conversion  to  anisotropic  refinement  produced an R-factor of8.8%. At this stage, a total of36 hydrogen atoms were located  from the difference Fourier map. The positional parameters and isotropic temperature  factors of hydrogen atoms were refined in the final stages. The final R-factoris 6.5% with  the maximum residual electron densities less than -0.32 e/ Nand 0.35 e/ A3 . Atomic  scattering factors were calculated by analytical form using coefficients in International  Tables  for  X-ray Crystallography (20).  The  final  atomic coordinates  of the non  hydrogen atoms are listed in Table I and their anisotropic temperature factors are  listed in Table Sl. The atomic coordinates and the isotropic temperature factors of the  hydrogen atoms are listed in Table S2. The bond distances and angles are listed in  Table S3. Tables Sl, S2 & S3  are available from the author (AHJW) upon request.  Data Collection and Structural Solution

Ring A  has  a  half chair pucker conformation with  C8  atom  farthest,  0.49 A for  STEFF-I and 0.45 A for STEF-11 from the mean plane ofC7, C6a, ClOa and ClO  atoms of ring A  This conformation places the C 13 methyl and 07 hydroxyl groups  in the axial positions on the same side of ring A, while the axial 08 methoxygroup is  on the opposite side to Cl3 and 07 of ring A The methoxy group in both steffimycin  molecules has a significantly higher temperature factor;  as indicated by the large  thermal ellipsoid in Figure 2.  This suggests that the 08 methoxy group of steffimycin  may rotate about the C8-08 bond in solution. The relative position of these two  oxygen atoms (07 and 08) in ring A may be important in the binding of steffimycin

The structures of the two independent steffimycin molecules (STEF-l and STEF-11)  are shown in Figure 2. The differences between STEF-l and STEF-11 lie in torsional angle differences  at the glycosyllinkage, causing a slight orientation difference of the sugar and also  in the  planarity of the  fused  rings  B-D.  Rings  B-D  are  planar,  though  the  rms  deviations  from  planarity for  STEF-l is  0.064 A,  while  it is  0.018  A for  STEF-11  through  the core  rings  B-D without including the  exocyclic  atoms. They clearly  show that the tautomeric structure in Figure l is the predominate form in that C5-05  (1.24 A) and Cl2-012 (1.22 A) are of the keto forms and C4-04 (1.40 A) and C6-06  (1.34 A) are of the phenolic forms. Most of the bond distances and angles (listed in  Table S3) agree well with other anthracyclines such as steffimycin B (17), daunorubicin  (27) and nogalamycin (28). Energy minimization of these models were done using XPLOR (22).  The partial  charges of steffimycin were calculated using the semi-empirical AM l Hamiltonian  of AMPAC program (23,  24), while the force  field  parameters of steffimycin were  assigned from representative molecular fragments. The DNA force field parameters  used in this work, are packaged with XPLOR and are those ofNilsson and Karplus  (25).  The  empirical  energy  function  included  bond,  angle,  dihedral,  impropers,  nonbonded energy terms.  The nonbonded energy term  included van der Waals,  electrostatic and explicit hydrogen bond energy terms. The hydrogen bond parameters  provided were incrementally scaled to decrease unacceptably large DNA distortions. All  polar hydrogens were included in the calculation, and non-polar hydrogens were  included through an extended atom representation. The Powell algorithm (26) was  employed for the energy minimization and the minimization was continued until  the gradient converged. The  molecular structure of several  anthracycline drugs,  including steffimycin  B  (17),  daunorubicin  (27),  nogalamycin  (28),  and  carminomycin  (29),  have  been  solved.  In addition,  the  complexes of daunorubicin, doxorubicin  and several  of  their derivatives with DNA oligonucleotides have been crystallized and their three  dimensional structures analyzed (8-10). More recently, the structure of nogalamycin  d[CGT(pS)ACG)] provided us with exquisite details ofhownogalamycin, with two  bulky sugars on both ends of the molecule, interacts with DNA in both grooves of  the double helix (11).

We have also examined the stacking interactions of steffimycin B in a different crystal  lattice (17). We were surprised to see that steffimycin B has a nearly identical stacking  pattern in the P 212121 crystal as the two steffimycins in the present structure (in the  P1  crystal), despite the fact that steffimycin and steffimycin B exist in different crystal  lattices. This observation strongly suggests that this recurring stacking pattern is a  characteristic feature of steffimycin, and possibly of anthracycline antibiotics in  general. This property is consistent with the intercalation interactions of anthracycline  antibiotics, e.g., daunorubicin (8-10) and nogalamycin (11-15) in DNA In the structure  of all  anthracycline-DNA complexes  studied  so  far,  the  aglycone  chromophore  penetrates the DNA double helix such that its long direction is almost perpendicular to

The interactions between the aglycone chromophores are shown in details in Figure  SA and 5B. Two STEF-l molecules in adjacent unit cells in the c-axis direction are  linked together with four hydrogen bonds. Each molecule uses the 04, 06, phenolic  hydroxyl groups (at x, y, z) as donors from one edge of the steffimycin to form two  hydrogen bonds to the 012 and 010 keto oxygens of another steffimycin (at x, y,  I +z). The hydrogen bond distances are 04(1)--012(1*) 3.10 A and 06(1)--010(1*)  3.04A(the I* molecule is atx, y, -1 +z; see Table III). In this manner, the steffimycins  (STEF-l) form an infinite sheet along the c- axis direction. The other independent  steffimycin, STEF-11, is stacked over those hydrogen-bonded STEF-I's.lt is interesting  to  note  that the  steffimycins  are  positioned  such  that the  exocyclic  polarizable  oxygen atoms (05, 06, 011) from STEF-11 are over the aromatic rings B & D from  STEF I (Figure 5A). An almost identical situation exists for the stacking of STEF -1  over  the  hydrogen-bonded  STEF-11  sheet  (Figure  5B).  However,  the  hydrogen  bonds  in  the  sheet  of STEF-II's  appear  to  be  somewhat  weaker  with  04(11)-- 0 12(11*), 06(11)--0 10(11*) distances of3.25 A and 3.22 A respectively (Table III). The  two  sheets  (STEF-l  and STEF-11)  interleaf each  other along the  (110)  direction  (Figure 4).  Intermolecular Interactions

The crystal packing interactions of the molecules are shown in Figure 4. It can be  seen  that the  triclinic  unit cell  is  segregated  into  two  regions.  The  hydrophobic  region consists of the aglycone chromophores of the two independent steffimycins,  which  form  intermolecular hydrogen  bonds  resulting  a  large  sheet of aromatic  plane. Successive sheets are stacked along the (110) direction. In contrast, the sugar  moieties are embedded in a  hydrophilic channel with  three water molecules and  one 2-MPD molecule interspersed throughout the channel.  of a steffimycin-DNAcomplex, eitherin solution by NMR or in crystal by x-ray dif  fraction. However, note that steffimycin has more extensive modifications in ring A,  with C7, C8, C9 and CIO positions having different substituents on them. Further,  C9  atom  has  the  same  chirality  as  that  in  nogalamycin.  Consequently,  we  are  inclined to believe that steffimycin would behave as nogalamycin in its DNA binding  property and base sequence preference. This  feature  was  considered in the con  struction of the model of steffimycin-DNA complex and it will be discussed later in  the paper.  A surprising finding was that a well-resolved 2-MPD molecule is located in the solvent  channel. It should be pointed out that the 2-MPD solvent used in the crystallization  experiment is a racemic mixture of two enantiomers. We can not say whether both  enantiomers have been incorporated in the crystal lattice, i.e., a two-fold disordered  2-MPD molecule in the solvent channel, or only one enantiomer is used. We have  assigned the D-isomerto the 2-MPD in the crystal structure on the basis of the hydrogen  bonding pattern. But this can not be taken as unequivocal assignment. Finally, we  have attempted to crystallize the steffimycin using pure D-isomer of 2-MPD. We  were not able to obtain the same crystal of sufficient quality for x-ray analysis.

The ring A and the sugar of steffimycin are comparatively hydrophilic. The 09 hydroxyl  group of ring A donates a hydrogen bond to the 01 1 of the sugar from the steffimycin at  x, y, 1 + z for both steffimycins, with the respective hydrogen bond distances of2.93 A for  STEF-l and 3.15 A for STEF-11. The hydroxyl groups (03 1  and 041 )  of the STEF-l form  reciprocal hydrogen bonds with the same hydroxyl groups (04 1 and 03 1 )  ofSTEF-11  (Table III). These hydroxyl groups are also  hydrogen bonded to water molecules  and 2-MPD [03 1(1)--0lW, 03 1(1)--02W, 03 1(11)--03M, 04 1(11)--0lW; Table III].  the C 11 -C 1 I vectors ofthe two GC base pairs above and below the intercalator. In the  way, the exocyclic nitrogen and oxygen atoms from the GC base pairs are stacked  over the  aromatic portion of the  aglycone,  and conversely the  exocyclic  oxygen  atoms of the anthracycline drugs are stacked over the purine/pyrimidine rings.

Figure 6 shows the 3-D structure of the central four base pairs plus drug of the 1:1 complex  of steffimycin with a DNA decamer duplex with the sequence of d(CGTACGTACG),  drawn using ORTEP-11 (31 ). This model is constructed based on a number of building  principles  derived  from  the  structures  of other  anthracycline-DNA  complexes  which have been determined by x-ray crystallography and NMR previously (8-15).  First, the elongated aglycone chromophore skewers the DNA molecule such that it  is almost perpendicular to the C 1' -C 1' vectors of the two GC base pairs above and  below the intercalator. The drug spans the two grooves of the helix with the sugar in the  minor groove and the D-ring protruding in the major groove. The A-ring is puckered and  a consequence of this pucker is that the 08 methoxy is in the axial position pointing  perpendicular to the plane of the drug. Its oxygen may be in a position to receive a  hydrogen bond from the N2 amino group of a guanine base.  Steffimycin and Its Binding to DNA  It is interesting to compare the binding interactions of(C II  G) 0  and (C II  G )N models  derived from the starting structures of daunorubicin-DNA (8) and nogalamycin-DNA  complexes (11 ). These two models seem to have converged to similar structures. The  long dimension of the aglycone lies across the base pairs reaching both grooves. The  hydrogen bonding pattern in both models is  similar with  three  hydrogen  bonds  being formed in the minor groove. The 08 of the methoxy group of drug receives a  hydrogen bond from the N2 ofG 16, while N2 ofG6 donates a hydrogen bond to the 07  atom of drug sugar and 03' of drug sugar to 02 ofTI. The (T II A) model of steffimycin  on the other hand has only two hydrogen bonds being formed between the drug and  DNA in the minor groove.

The tight fit of drug to DNA results in the distortion of the DNA helix, most prominently  the buckle of base pairs at the CpG intercalation site. The helical twist angles of the  CpG step across the intercalator in the (C II  G)0  and (C II  G)N  models are 34.3 o  &  37.9°  respectively, suggesting very little change in winding at the intercalation site,  while the average helical twist of the entire helix is  35.5°  &  36.1 o  respectively. As  pointed out earlier(lO,ll), the overall unwinding angle of the DNA helix due to the  intercalation of an anthracycline drug is significantly lower than the value observed  for the simple intercalator ethidium ( -26°)(30). We suggested (11) that it may be a  common feature of all anthracycline drugs. The total angular curvature of the DNA  helix axis is 3.2 o  as a result of the drug binding to DNA  Figure 7 shows the van der Waals view of the entire model. The central CG base pair  together with a common portion of the drug of the present model has a root mean  squares deviation of0.948 A from the nogalamycin-d(CGTACG) crystal structure.

The minimized models have similar total energies of- 549.3 Kcal/mole and -552.3  Kcal/mole for the (C II  G)0  and (C II  G~ models  respectively.  These two  models  have a lower energy than that of the minimized (T II A) model of steffimycin and of the  two B-DNA duplexes alone by at least 40 Kcal/mole. The analysis of the interaction  energy  between  steffimycin  and  DNA in (ciiG)0 ,  (ciiG)N and (TIIA)  models  shows a lower energy for the binding of steffimycin to the CpG step, largely accounted  for by the hydrogen bond energy component. Stereochemically, there are only two  relevant hydrogen bonds betvireen drug and DNA when steffimycin is intercalated  at the TpA step whereas there are three relevant hydrogen bonds at the CpG step.  This suggests a preference of steffimycin for intercalation at a CpG site in DNA like  the anthracyclines daunorubicin (8)  and nogalamycin (11).  Simulations  of the  models  of drug-DNA complexes  in  vacuo  for  50  ps  at 300K,  without constraints were not as successful because the DNA base pairs at the end of  the helix tended to fall into the major groove, causing the ends of the helix to bend  significantly. This artifact, termed as" end effect", could not be satisfactorily removed.  It was concluded that these simulations must be done with adequate representation  of counterions and hydration. As this sort of detailed simulation was beyond the  scope of this paper, a systematic study on the molecular dynamic simulations of this  molecule complexed to DNA will be carried out later. The molecular structure of steffimycin is of interest as it adds to our database of 3- dimensional molecular structures of anthracyclines. Based on our present study we  propose that the stacking interactions of anthracyclines in general have the anthracene  moiety stacked over the partially charged polarizable exocyclic oxygen and nitrogen  atoms. This is very similar to the stacking interaction of anthracyclines as they intercalate  with DNA. The molecular modelling of steffimycin with DNA suggests a preference  of the drug molecule to intercalate at the CpG step. The modelling was done using  the knowledge obtained from the structural studies of other related anthracycline  drug-DNA complexes.  This  approach  is  useful  for  designing new anthracycline  drugs as more structural analyses like this would aid narrowing down the possibilities  while designing new synthetic compounds with different DNA binding properties.  20.
